    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-06-20T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-06-20T03:00:00-05:00" n="484"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.1123 Thomson, J. C./6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-06-20T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 20, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 20—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>392. Department’s 199, June 18, 4 p.m., assault on Dr. J. C. Thomson in Nanking.
                    Appropriate representations were made by me in an interview with the Vice
                    Minister for Foreign Affairs today supported by an <hi rend="italic"
                        >aide-mémoire</hi>. I took occasion to add that irrespective of the results
                    of an investigation my Government feels that the causes and circumstances which
                    give rise to such incidents might readily be prevented if the Japanese military
                    authorities at Nanking were to impress upon Japanese soldiers the importance of
                    maintaining toward American nationals an attitude of civility. I spoke,
                    furthermore, of the deplorable effect on American public opinion and therefore
                    on Japanese-American relations of such incidents, pointing out that they
                    inevitably served to set back whatever favorable effects were created by recent
                    signs of a desire on the part of the Japanese Government to give greater
                    consideration to American interests in China.</p>
                <p>The Vice Minister expressed himself as in full concurrence with this view and
                    promised an immediate investigation of the Thomson case.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai for Hankow and Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
